Stow, writing about 1598, says, ‘ This chureh was again newly re· built in the reign of Richard 11 and king Henry lv. John Gower‚ a learned gentleman and a famous poet, but no knight‚ as some have mistaken it, was then an especial benefactor to that work, and was there buried in the north side of the said church, in the chapel of St. John, where he founded a chantry. He lieth under a tomb of stone with his image also of stone being over him.
